                    pickles,&rdquo; McVries said. His scar flashed very white in the dying daylight. &ldquo;You
                    don&rsquo;t really mind the thought of dying, do you, Olson? Like the poet also said, it
                    ain&rsquo;t the dying, it&rsquo;s laying in the grave so long. Is that what&rsquo;s bugging you,
                    booby?&rdquo; McVries began to trumpet. &ldquo;Well, cheer up, Charlie! There&rsquo;s a brighter
                    day com&mdash;&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;Leave him alone,&rdquo; Baker said quietly.<br />&ldquo;Why
                    should I? He&rsquo;s busy convincing himself he can crap out any time he feels like it. That if he
                    just lays down and dies, it won&rsquo;t be as bad as everyone makes out. Well, I&rsquo;m not going
                    to let him get away with it.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;If he doesn&rsquo;t die, you will,&rdquo; Garraty
                    said.<br />&ldquo;Yeah, I&rsquo;m remembering,&rdquo; McVries said, and gave Garraty his tight,
                    slanted smile ... only this time there was absolutely no humor in it at all. Suddenly McVries
                    looked furious, and Garraty was almost afraid of him. &ldquo;He&rsquo;s the one that&rsquo;s
                    forgetting. This turkey here.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to do it anymore,&rdquo; Olson
                    said hollowly, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sick of it.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;Raring to rip,&rdquo; McVries said,
                    turning on him. &ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t that what you said? Fuck it, then. Why don&rsquo;t you just fall
                    down and die then?&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;Leave him alone,&rdquo; Garraty said.<br />&ldquo;Listen,
                    Ray&mdash;&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;No, you listen. One Barkovitch is enough. Let him do it his own way.
                    No musketeers, remember.&rdquo;<br />McVries smiled again. &ldquo;Okay, Garraty. You win.&rdquo;<br />Olson
                    didn&rsquo;t say anything. He just kept picking them up and laying them down.</p>
