        <li class="gad msg bp">
            <a class="open" href="javascript:void(0)">p185 Garraty almost dies #2 (laughing fit), McVries saves Garraty
                #2 (picks him up), Broken Promise #1</a>
            <div style="display:none">
                <p>You&rsquo;re going to have hysterics, oh my God, don&rsquo;t let it get you, think about Gribble ...
                    and don&rsquo;t ... don&rsquo;t let ... don&rsquo;t ...<br />But it was happening. The laughter
                    came roaring out of him until his stomach was knotted and cramped and he was walking bent-legged
                    and somebody was hollering at him, screaming at him over the roar of the crowd. It was McVries.
                    &ldquo;Ray! Ray! What is it? You all right?&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;They&rsquo;re funny!&rdquo; He was
                    nearly weeping with laughter now. &ldquo;Pete, Pete, they&rsquo;re so funny, it&rsquo;s just ...
                    just ... that they&rsquo;re so funny!&rdquo;<br />A hard-faced little girl in a dirty sundress sat
                    on the ground, pouty-mouthed and frowning. She made a horrible face as they passed. Garraty nearly
                    collapsed with laughter and drew a warning. It was strange&mdash;in spite of all the noise he could
                    still hear the warnings clearly.<br />I could die, he thought. I could just die laughing,
                    wouldn&rsquo;t that be a scream?<br />Collie was still smiling gaily and waving and cursing
                    spectators and newsmen roundly, and that seemed funniest of all. Garraty fell to his knees and was
                    warned again. He continued to laugh in short, barking spurts, which were all his laboring lungs
                    would allow.<br />&ldquo;He&rsquo;s gonna puke!&rdquo; someone cried in an ecstasy of delight.
                    &ldquo;Watch &rsquo;im, Alice, he&rsquo;s gonna puke!&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;Garraty! Garraty for
                    God&rsquo;s sake!&rdquo; McVries was yelling. He got an arm around Garraty&rsquo;s back and hooked
                    a hand into his armpit. Somehow he yanked him to his feet and Garraty stumbled on.<br />&ldquo;Oh
                    God,&rdquo; Garraty gasped. &ldquo;Oh Jesus Christ they&rsquo;re killing me. I ... I can&rsquo;t
                    ...&rdquo; He broke into loose, trickling laughter once more. His knees buckled. McVries ripped him
                    to his feet once more. Garraty&rsquo;s collar tore. They were both warned. That&rsquo;s my last
                    warning, Garraty thought dimly. I&rsquo;m on my way to see that fabled farm. Sorry, Jan, I ...<br />&ldquo;Come
                    on, you turkey, I can&rsquo;t lug you!&rdquo; McVries hissed.<br />&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t do
                    it,&rdquo; Garraty gasped. &ldquo;My wind&rsquo;s gone, I&mdash;&rdquo;<br />McVries slapped him
                    twice quickly, forehand on the right cheek, backhand on the left. Then he walked away quickly, not
                    looking back.<br />The laughter had gone out of him now but his gut was jelly, his lungs empty and
                    seemingly unable to refill. He staggered drunkenly along, weaving, trying to find his wind. Black
                    spots danced in front of his eyes, and a part of him understood how close to fainting he was. His
                    one foot fetched against his other foot, he stumbled, almost fell, and somehow kept his balance.<br />If
                    I fall, I die. I&rsquo;ll never get up.<br />They were watching him. The crowd was watching him.
                    The cheers had died away to a muted, almost sexual murmur. They were waiting for him to fall down.<br />He
                    walked on, now concentrating only on putting one foot out in front of the other. Once, in the
                    eighth grade, he had read a story by a man named Ray Bradbury, and this story was about the crowds
                    that gather at the scenes of fatal accidents, about how these crowds always have the same faces,
                    and about how they seem to know whether the wounded will live or die. I&rsquo;m going to live a
                    little longer, Garraty told them. I&rsquo;m going to live. I&rsquo;m going to live a little longer.<br />He
                    made his feet rise and fall to the steady cadence in his head. He blotted everything else out, even
                    Jan. He was not aware of the head, or of Collie Parker, or of Freaky D&rsquo;Allessio. He was not
                    even aware of the steady dull pain in his feet and the frozen stiffness of the hamstring muscles
                    behind his knees. The thought pounded in his mind like a big kettledrum. Like a heartbeat. Live a
                    little longer. Live a little longer. Live a little longer. Until the words themselves became
                    meaningless and signified nothing.<br />It was the sound of the guns that brought him out of it.<br />In
                    the crowd-hushed stillness the sound was shockingly loud and he could hear someone screaming. Now
                    you know, he thought, you live long enough to hear the sound of the guns, long enough to hear
                    yourself screaming&mdash;<br />But one of his feet kicked a small stone then and there was pain and
                    it wasn&rsquo;t him that had bought it, it was 64, a pleasant, smiling boy named Frank Morgan. They
                    were dragging Frank Morgan off the road. His glasses were dragging and bouncing on the pavement,
                    still hooked stubbornly over one ear. The left lens had been shattered.<br />&ldquo;I&rsquo;m not
                    dead,&rdquo; he said dazedly. Shock hit him in a warm blue wave, threatening to turn his legs to
                    water again.<br />&ldquo;Yeah, but you ought to be,&rdquo; McVries said.<br />&ldquo;You saved
                    him,&rdquo; Olson said, turning it into a curse.&ldquo;Why did you do that? Why did you do
                    that?&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
