                    sit down.&rdquo;<br />Terror pounded Garraty&rsquo;s chest. &ldquo;No! No way!&rdquo;<br />McVries
                    looked at him for a moment, then smiled again and shook his head. He sat down, cross legged on the
                    pavement. He looked like a world-beaten monk. The scar on his cheek was a white slash in the rainy
                    gloom.<br />&ldquo;No!&rdquo; Garraty screamed.<br />He tried to pick McVries up, but, thin as he
                    was, McVries was much too heavy. McVries wouldn&rsquo;t even look at him. His eyes were shut. And
                    suddenly two of the soldiers were wrenching McVries away from him. They were putting their guns to
                    McVries&rsquo;s head.<br />&ldquo;No!&rdquo; Garraty screamed again. &ldquo;Me! Me! Shoot
                    me!&rdquo;<br />But instead, they gave him his third warning.<br />McVries opened his eyes and
                    smiled again. The next instant, he was gone.</p>
            </div>
        </li>
        <li class="gad">
            <a class="open" href="javascript:void(0)">p387 Garraty almost dies #13 (wave of dizziness)</a>
            <div style="display:none">
                <p>&ldquo;The king wasn&rsquo;t digging it, thinking no one was good enough for his daughter Gwen, the
                    world-famous Lady Fair, but the Lady Fair loved the White Knight so much that she threatened to run
                    away into the Wildwoods if ... if ...&rdquo; <strong>A wave of dizziness
                        rode over him darkly</strong>, making him feel as if he were floating. The roar of the crowd
                    came to him
                    like the boom of the sea down a long, cone-shaped tunnel. Then it passed, but slowly.</p>
